In this section, we first introduce the selection of the pretrained multimodal foundation model (Sec. 3.1), followed by the multimodal-text pair filtering and optimization pipeline (Sec. 3.2), and finally present the hierarchical decoupled adaptation training framework (Sec. 3.3).
\subsection{Multimodal Foundation Model Selection}
The research on multimodal large models has developed rapidly, but it still primarily focuses on the text-image modalities. We aim to select a pretrained large model that supports a wider range of modalities to provide multimodal mixed retrieval capabilities applicable to industries such as healthcare, education, and manufacturing. OneLLM is capable of cross-modal semantic understanding across eight different modalities, including text, image, audio, video, point cloud, depth/normal maps, IMU data, and fMRI brain activity signals, offering a strong foundation for our retrieval framework. To better introduce the training scheme of our retrieval model, we first provide a brief overview of OneLLM’s architecture and training process.
OneLLM consists of four key components. First, modality-specific tokenizers convert inputs from various modalities into token sequences suitable for Transformer-based processing, usually implemented as a single convolutional layer. Second, a universal encoder—built on a pretrained vision encoder—processes token sequences from all modalities in a unified manner before passing them to the next module. Third, the Universal Projection Module (UPM) projects features from different modalities into the text embedding space of the large language model, facilitating cross-modal fusion through a mixture-of-experts projection mechanism that enhances adaptability across modalities. Finally, the large language model employs a decoder architecture with autoregressive generation to achieve multimodal fusion and understanding for downstream tasks.
\subsection{Multimodal-Text Pair Filtering}
\begin{figure*}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{CameraReady/LaTeX/img/data.png}
    \caption{The overall pipeline for multimodal-text pair filtering and enhancement. The process consists of two phases: (i) Similarity Filtering—initial modality-text pairs (from images, videos, audio, and point clouds) are evaluated using pretrained multimodal encoders, and are filtered based on cosine similarity thresholds to retain high-quality positive samples and mine hard negatives; (ii) Description Enhancement—a LLM is employed to enrich, restructure, and optionally translate retained captions to produce high-quality modality-to-text description pairs with greater semantic granularity and consistency.}
    \label{fig:enter-label}
\end{figure*}
High-quality modality-text paired data (X-caption pairs) play a crucial role in enhancing cross-modal alignment capabilities during multimodal retrieval model training. However, existing multimodal datasets vary significantly in quality and often contain noisy, weakly paired, or even incorrect matches. Therefore, prior to training modality embeddings, it is essential to perform meticulous data filtering and augmentation to ensure that the final training data exhibit stronger cross-modal consistency and richer semantic information. Accordingly, we construct high-quality X-caption pairs from publicly available multimodal datasets and enhance the granularity of their textual descriptions, as illustrated in Figure 5.
Specifically, we first collect initial modality-text paired data for each modality from open-source datasets. We then employ a multi-stage data filtering strategy that leverages state-of-the-art multimodal large models for data evaluation and selection:  
(1) \textbf{Image-text data:} Similarity between images and texts is computed using pretrained models with strong vision-language alignment abilities such as CLIP, BLIP-2, and SigLIP.  
(2) \textbf{Video-text data:} Video-text similarity is measured using models like Flamingo or Video-LLaMA.  
(3) \textbf{Audio-text data:} Audio-text alignment is assessed via AudioBind and Whisper.  
(4) \textbf{Point cloud-text data:} 3D point cloud and text similarity is evaluated using Point-BERT and 3D-Language MLLMs.
During filtering, we adopt a two-stage similarity-based strategy to guarantee data quality while enhancing model discriminability. First, we filter the raw paired data to retain high-quality cross-modal aligned samples. Then, we mine hard negative samples from unpaired data to improve model robustness in contrastive learning.
After the initial filtering, we further optimize textual descriptions using large language models (LLMs) to achieve finer-grained semantic expressiveness. This stage includes:  
(1) \textbf{Automatic description enrichment:} Using LLMs such as GPT-4, LLaMA-3, or Mistral to supplement original captions with more detailed information (e.g., expanding “a dog on the grass” to “a golden retriever lying on the green grass, enjoying the sunshine”).  
(2) \textbf{Standardization of text style and format:} To ensure consistency, we prompt LLMs to rewrite all captions into a fixed structured format.  
(3) \textbf{Cross-lingual enhancement:} For English data, we introduce bilingual augmentation by generating equivalent Chinese descriptions with LLMs, enabling the model to support multilingual retrieval tasks in subsequent training.
After completing the above two steps, we compute a final quality score for each multimodal-text paired sample:
\begin{equation}
Q(x,t) = \alpha \cos{(\textbf{h}_x,\textbf{h}_t})  + \beta S_{\text{LLM}}  
\end{equation}
Where \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are weighting coefficients, and \(S_{\text{LLM-text}}\) denotes the quality score of the text descriptions generated by the LLM. We retain only the data samples with quality scores exceeding a predefined threshold for final training. This rigorous filtering and enhancement process ensures the high quality of the training data, thereby providing a solid data foundation for unified multimodal representation learning.
\subsection{Hierarchical Decoupled Adaptation Framework}
Existing multimodal large-model retrieval methods typically fine-tune the entire model directly using multimodal paired data to learn unified multimodal representations. However, this training approach often suffers from slow convergence and heavy dependence on large-scale paired datasets. To address these issues, we propose a hierarchical decoupled adaptation training framework that separates discriminative representation learning from unified multimodal representation learning, thereby reducing the difficulty of multimodal alignment and lessening reliance on extensive paired data.
Specifically, \textbf{in the first stage}, we fine-tune the large language model (LLM) using only textual data. This preserves the model's open-domain knowledge while enhancing its ability to learn discriminative textual representations for fine-grained retrieval. We employ sentence pairs from natural language inference (NLI) datasets for training. These datasets are modality-agnostic, cover diverse language reasoning scenarios, and include both Chinese and English sentences, thus improving the model’s generalization across languages, especially in understanding Chinese.
Each training sample consists of an input sentence \( x \), a semantically similar positive sentence \( x^+ \), and a semantically unrelated negative sentence \( x^- \). To guide the model to focus on core semantics, we prepend the prompt "\texttt{<text> \textbackslash n Please summarize the input sentence in one word:}" so that the model processes inputs more compactly and learns effective sentence embeddings. After encoding by the LLM, each sentence is mapped to an embedding vector: \( \mathbf{h}, \mathbf{h}_i^+, \mathbf{h}_i^- \).
We train the model with contrastive learning to optimize the LLM-generated text embeddings such that semantically similar sentences are pulled closer while dissimilar sentences are pushed apart. The contrastive loss is defined as
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{L} = -\log \frac{e^{\frac{\cos\left(\mathbf{h}_i, \mathbf{h}_i^+\right)}{\tau}}}{\sum_{j=1}^N \left( e^{\frac{\cos\left(\mathbf{h}_i, \mathbf{h}_j^+\right)}{\tau}} + e^{\frac{\cos\left(\mathbf{h}_i, \mathbf{h}_j^-\right)}{\tau}} \right)}
\end{equation}
where \(\cos(\cdot, \cdot)\) denotes the cosine similarity between embeddings, \(\tau\) is a temperature hyperparameter, and \(N\) is the number of samples in the batch. The goal is to increase the similarity between each input embedding \(\mathbf{h}_i\) and its corresponding positive embedding \(\mathbf{h}_i^+\), while simultaneously pushing it away from other positive (\(\mathbf{h}_j^+\)) and negative (\(\mathbf{h}_j^-\)) samples in the batch. This objective enhances the discriminative quality of the learned text representations, which is critical for fine-grained retrieval.
This stage fine-tunes the LLM's textual embedding capability on top of the pretrained multimodal large language model (MLLM), producing higher-quality text representations better suited for retrieval. Since the MLLM has already learned to roughly align different modalities into the LLM’s input text semantic space during pretraining, enhancing the LLM’s retrieval ability within the textual space provides a more stable foundation for unified encoding of multimodal features in subsequent training. This approach enables more efficient learning of multimodal retrieval features and mitigates the negative impact of low-quality LLM-generated text embeddings on cross-modal representation learning.
\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{CameraReady/LaTeX/img/mask.png}
    \caption{
Illustration of the self-attention masking strategies used in the second stage of OneLLM for fine-grained cross-modal alignment.
The \textbf{Uni-modal Self-Attention Mask} supports \textit{Modality-Text Contrastive Learning (X-TC)} by isolating intra-modal and intra-text dependencies to extract discriminative features for alignment.
The \textbf{Bi-directional Self-Attention Mask} enables \textit{Modality-Text Matching (X-TM)}, allowing full interaction between modality and text tokens for binary alignment classification.
The \textbf{Multi-modal Causal Self-Attention Mask} facilitates \textit{Modality-Grounded Text Generation (X-TG)} by autoregressively generating text based on modality cues, while preventing information leakage from future tokens.
Together, these complementary objectives form a generation-discrimination collaborative optimization framework for unified cross-modal representation learning.
}
    \label{fig:enter-label}
\end{figure}
\textbf{In the second stage}, based on the overall architecture of OneLLM, we project multimodal data into the LLM’s embedding space through a universal encoder and a universal projection module. We then achieve fine-grained cross-modal semantic alignment using a generation-discrimination collaborative optimization framework.
To ensure alignment of different modalities within a shared semantic space, we design a collaborative optimization architecture that integrates three complementary loss functions, enhancing the model’s unified cross-modal representation capability:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Modality-Text Contrastive Learning (X-TC)}  
   To optimize modality embeddings such that paired modality-text features are pulled closer while unpaired samples are pushed farther apart.  
  Method: The modality data is fed into the LLM along with a textual prompt, e.g., “Summarize the discriminative information of this [modality] in one word,” where [modality] could be “image” or “video segment.” The modality embedding is extracted from the last-layer [EOS] token of the LLM output and contrasted against the text embedding via a contrastive loss:  
\begin{equation}
\small
    \mathcal{L}_{X-TC} = -\log \frac{e^{\frac{\cos\left(h_x, h_t\right)}{\tau}}}{\sum_{j=1}^N \left( e^{\frac{\cos\left(h_x, h_j^+\right)}{\tau}} + e^{\frac{\cos\left(h_x, h_j^-\right)}{\tau}} \right)}
\end{equation}
  where \(\tau\) is the temperature hyperparameter, and \(\mathbf{h}_x\), \(\mathbf{h}_t\) denote the modality and text embeddings respectively.
  \item \textbf{Modality-Text Matching (X-TM)}  
   To optimize the LLM’s binary classification logits, enabling it to determine whether a modality and text description are paired.  
  Method: The modality data and corresponding text are input together into the LLM with the prompt: “Does this [modality] match the text description?” The logits at the [EOS] token position are used to compute the cross-entropy loss over the “Yes/No” tokens:  
% \begin{equation}
%     \mathcal{L}_{X-TM} = -\sum_{i=1}^N \left[ y_i \log P(y_i) + (1 - y_i) \log \left(1 - P(y_i)\right) \right]
% \end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    \small
    \mathcal{L}_{X-TM} = -\sum_{i=1}^N \left[ y_i \log P(y_i) + (1 - y_i) \log \left(1 - P(y_i)\right) \right]
\end{equation}
  where \(y_i\) is the ground truth label indicating whether the pair matches.
  \item \textbf{Modality-Text Generation (X-TG)}  
   To train the LLM to autoregressively generate the text description conditioned on modality information.  
  Method: Using next-token prediction, the model is trained to generate the correct text caption given the modality prefix:  
  \begin{equation}
  \small
\mathcal{L}_{X-TG} = -\sum_{t=1}^T \log P(y_t \mid y_{<t}, q_m)
\end{equation}
  where \(w_t\) is the \(t\)-th token in the text description and \(q_m\) represents the modality input.
\end{enumerate}
We collaboratively optimize three tasks: modality-text contrastive learning (X-TC), modality-text matching (X-TM), and modality-text generation (X-TG). Through this, our multimodal retrieval model effectively addresses fine-grained semantic degradation in cross-modal alignment, learning discriminative and high-quality unified representations within a shared semantic space.
