\section{Experiments}
We conduct our experiments on a machine equipped with 8 NVIDIA RTX A6000 GPUs. For the backbone language model, we adopt the LLaMA2-7B~\cite{llma2} model and perform full-parameter fine-tuning.
Due to time and computational resource constraints, we have currently completed only the first stage of our proposed hierarchical decoupled adaptation framework, along with an evaluation of its effectiveness. Specifically, inspired by LLM2CLIP~\cite{wu2024llmclip}, we construct a purely textual contrastive learning dataset based on the CC-3M dataset~\cite{CC3M}. In this dataset, each image is annotated with one original caption, three long captions, and three short captions. We treat the long and short captions corresponding to the same image as a positive pair, while captions from other images serve as negative samples.
To evaluate the effectiveness of this first-stage training, we follow LLM2CLIP's setup and conduct a text-only retrieval task. We use the MSCOCO 5K dataset~\cite{mscoco} for testing and compare the top-1 retrieval accuracy before and after fine-tuning. Experimental results show that the fine-tuned model achieves a 5.31\% improvement in top-1 accuracy on MSCOCO 5K. While the improvement is modest, it indicates the effectiveness of the proposed textual contrastive training. The limited gain may be attributed to factors such as the choice of dataset and training configurations, which can be further optimized in future work.
